1 …
2 (d) Transportation Investment Strategy Formula. – Funds subject to the Formula shall be
3 distributed as follows:follows, with at least twenty percent (20%) of the funds distributed to
4 non-highway projects:
5 (1) Statewide Strategic Mobility Projects. – Forty percent (40%) Thirty percent
6 (30%) of the funds subject to this section shall be used for Statewide Strategic
7 Mobility Projects:
8 a. Criteria. – Transportation-related quantitative criteria shall be used by
9 the Department to rank highway projects that address cost-effective
10 Statewide Strategic Mobility needs and promote economic and
11 employment growth. The criteria for selection of Statewide Strategic
12 Mobility Projects shall utilize a numeric scale of 100 points, based on
13 consideration of the following quantitative criteria:
14 1. Benefit cost.
15 2. Congestion.
16 3. Safety.
17 4. Economic competitiveness.
18 5. Freight.
19 6. Multimodal.
20 7. Pavement Infrastructure condition.
21 8. Lane width.
22 9. Shoulder width.
23 10. Accessibility and connectivity to employment centers,
24 essential services, tourist destinations, or military installations.
25 11. Vehicle miles traveled.
26 12. Environmental quality.
27 …
28 (2) Regional Impact Projects. – Thirty percent (30%) Forty percent (40%) of the
29 funds subject to this section shall be used for Regional Impact Projects and
30 allocated by population of Distribution Regions based on the most recent
31 estimates certified by the Office of State Budget and Management:
32 a. Criteria. – A combination of transportation-related quantitative
33 criteria, qualitative criteria, and local input shall be used to rank
34 Regional Impact Projects involving highways projects that address
35 cost-effective needs from a region-wide perspective and promote
36 economic growth. Local input is defined as the rankings identified by
37 the Department's Transportation Division Engineers, Metropolitan
38 Planning Organizations, and Rural Transportation Planning
39 Organizations. Transportation Division Engineer local input scoring
40 shall take into account public comments. The Department shall ensure
41 that the public has a full opportunity to submit public comments, by
42 widely available notice to the public, an adequate time period for input,
43 and public hearings. Board of Transportation input shall be in
44 accordance with G.S. 136-189.11(g)(1) and G.S. 143B-350(g). The
45 criteria utilized for selection of Regional Impact Projects shall be
46 based thirty percent (30%) on local input and seventy percent (70%)
47 on consideration of a numeric scale of 100 points based on the
48 following quantitative criteria:
49 1. Benefit cost.
50 2. Congestion.
51 3. Safety.
