30 SECTION 4. G.S. 153A-145.1 is repealed.
31 SECTION 5. G.S. 160A-204 is repealed.
32 SECTION 6. G.S. 160D-804 reads as rewritten:
33 "§ 160D-804. Contents and requirements of regulation.
34 (a) Purposes. – A subdivision regulation may provide for the orderly growth and
35 development of the local government; for the coordination of transportation networks and
36 utilities within proposed subdivisions with existing or planned streets and highways streets,
37 highways, sidewalks, bicycle lanes, bus stops, transit infrastructure, and other transportation
38 facilities and with other public facilities; and for the distribution of population and traffic in a
39 manner that will avoid congestion and overcrowding and will create conditions that substantially
40 promote public health, safety, and general welfare.
41 …
42 (c) Transportation and Utilities. –
43 (1) The regulation may provide for the dedication of rights-of-way or easements
44 for street transportation and utility purposes, including the dedication of
45 rights-of-way pursuant to G.S. 136-66.10 or G.S. 136-66.11.
46 (2) A regulation adopted by a city may provide that in lieu of required street
47 transportation facility construction, a developer be required to provide funds
48 for city use for the construction of roads transportation facilities to serve the
49 occupants, residents, or invitees of the subdivision or development, and these
50 funds may be used for roads transportation facilities which serve more than
51 one subdivision or development within the area. All funds received by the city
House Bill 641-First Edition Page 7

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 pursuant to this subdivision shall be used only for development of roads,
2 transportation facilities, including design, land acquisition, and construction.
3 However, a city may undertake these activities in conjunction with the
4 Department of Transportation under an agreement between the city and the
5 Department of Transportation. The term "transportation facilities" includes
6 streets, sidewalks, bicycle lanes, bus stops, transit infrastructure, and other
7 facilities designed to assist the movement of people or goods from one place
8 to another.
9 (3) A regulation adopted by a county may provide that in lieu of required street
10 transportation facility construction, a developer may provide funds to a county
11 to be used for the development of roads transportation facilities to serve the
12 occupants, residents, or invitees of the subdivision or development. All funds
13 received by the county under this subdivision shall be transferred to a city to
14 be used solely for the development of roads, transportation facilities, including
15 design, land acquisition, and construction. Any city receiving funds from a
16 county under this subdivision is authorized to expend the funds outside its
17 corporate limits for the purposes specified in the agreement between the
18 municipality and the county.
19 (4) Any formula adopted by a local government to determine the amount of funds
20 the developer is to pay in lieu of required street transportation facility
21 construction shall be based on the trips generated from the subdivision or
22 development. The regulation may require a combination of partial payment of
23 funds and partial dedication of constructed streets transportation facilities
24 when the governing board determines that a combination is in the best
25 interests of the citizens of the area to be served.
26 …."
27 SECTION 7. G.S. 105-511.2 reads as rewritten:
28 "§ 105-511.2. Local election on adoption of sales and use tax.
29 (a) Resolution. – The board of commissioners of a county may direct the county board
30 of elections to conduct an advisory referendum within the county on the question of whether a
31 local sales and use tax at the rate of one-quarter percent (1/4%) up to one percent (1%) may be
32 levied in accordance with this Part. The election shall be held on a date jointly agreed upon by
33 the boards and shall be held on a date permitted by and in accordance with the procedures of
34 G.S. 163-287. The board of commissioners shall hold a public hearing on the question at least 30
35 days before the date the election is to be held.
36 (b) Ballot Question. – The form of the question to be presented on a ballot for a special
37 election concerning the levy of a tax authorized by this Article shall be:
38 "[ ] FOR [ ] AGAINST
39 One-quarter percent (1/4%) local sales and use taxes, in addition to the current local sales and
40 use taxes, to be used only for public transportation systems.""
41 SECTION 8. G.S. 160D-702(a) reads as rewritten:
42 "(a) A local government may adopt zoning regulations. Except as provided in subsections
43 (b) and (c) of this section, a zoning regulation may regulate and restrict the height, number of
44 stories, and size of buildings and other structures; the percentage of lots that may be occupied;
45 the size of yards, courts, and other open spaces; the density of population; the location and use
46 of buildings, structures, and land. A local government may regulate development, including
47 floating homes, over estuarine waters and over lands covered by navigable waters owned by the
48 State pursuant to G.S. 146-12. A zoning regulation shall provide density credits or severable
49 development rights for dedicated rights-of-way pursuant to G.S. 136-66.10 or G.S. 136-66.11.
50 Where appropriate, a zoning regulation may include requirements that street transportation
51 facility and utility rights-of-way be dedicated to the public, that provision be made of recreational
